2026 Regular Session ENROLLED
SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 176
BY SENATOR MIZELL
A RESOLUTION
To urge and request the Louisiana office of alcohol and tobacco control (ATC) and the
Board of Regents to jointly study the feasibility, security implications, and
administrative requirements of enabling student identification cards issued by
Louisiana postsecondary institutions to function as a form of digital identification
verification, and to report findings to the legislature.
WHEREAS, Louisiana's public and private postsecondary institutions issue student
identification cards that are widely used for campus access, meal plans, library services, and
other institutional functions; and
WHEREAS, rapid advancements in digital identity technology have expanded the
potential uses of secure, institution-issued identification credentials; and
WHEREAS, the office of alcohol and tobacco control is responsible for regulating
and enforcing state laws related to the sale of alcohol and tobacco products, including the
verification of legally required identification; and
WHEREAS, the Board of Regents oversees the state's public higher education
systems and maintains statewide policies related to student records, data security, and
institutional operations; and
WHEREAS, several states and private-sector entities have begun exploring or
implementing digital identification systems capable of verifying age or identity through
secure, encrypted platforms; and
WHEREAS, Louisiana may benefit from evaluating whether student identification
cards, physical or digital, could be integrated into a secure digital verification framework
that meets ATC standards for age and identity verification; and
WHEREAS, such a study would allow policymakers to assess potential benefits,
including convenience for students, modernization of verification processes, and reduction
of fraudulent identification, while also evaluating risks related to privacy, cybersecurity, and
institutional capacity.
